{"key":"post-9519916","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9519916</id>\n<content>It all depends on what you're wanting to see.&amp;nbsp; I use my stereo microscope far more often than my compound microscope.&amp;nbsp; Are you wanting to examine mycelium to see if it's mono or dikaryotic?&amp;nbsp; If so, you want a good compound microscope.&amp;nbsp; If you're wanting to examine gills and or ID molds, a good stereo microscope is what you want.&amp;nbsp; A stereo microscope is like a giant magnifying glass.&amp;nbsp; It looks at reflected light.&amp;nbsp; A compound microscope has the light below the specimen, so you see the light that shines through the object.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9520818</next>\n<prev>9519699</prev>\n<first>9519421</first>\n<last>9520914</last>\n<when>1230688376</when>\n<utime>12/31/08 03:52 AM</utime>\n</post>"}